******
[2] Cholera - Mexico (Veracruz, Hidalgo)
Date: Mon 25 Nov 2013
Source: WHO Global Alert and Response (GAR), Disease Outbreak News [edited]
http://www.who.int/csr/don/2013_11_25/en/index.html


The Ministry of Health in Mexico has reported an additional 4 cases of infection with _Vibrio cholerae_ O1 Ogawa. Of these, 3 are from the state of Veracruz and 1 from the state of Hidalgo.

Since the beginning of this outbreak in September 2013 to date, a total of 184 confirmed cases, including 1 death, of cholera has been reported in the country. Of these, 160 cases are from the state of Hidalgo, 11 from the state of Veracruz, 9 from the state of Mexico, 2 from the Federal District, and 2 from the state of San Luis Potosi.

An antimicrobial susceptibility test for the strain was conducted by the Institute of Epidemiological Diagnostics and Reference (InDRE) which demonstrated that the bacterium was susceptible to doxycycline and chloramphenicol, with reduced susceptibility to ciprofloxacin and resistance to trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole.

This is the 1st local transmission of cholera recorded since 2001 in Mexico. The genetic profile of the bacterium obtained from patients in Mexico presents high similarity (95 percent) with the strain that is currently circulating in 3 Caribbean countries (Haiti, Dominican Republic, and Cuba), and is different from the strain that had been circulating in Mexico during 1991-2001.

WHO does not recommend that any travel or trade restrictions be applied to Mexico with respect to this event.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Marianne Hopp

